04585nam a22007455i 9781501717208DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017172087 a10.7591/97815017172082doi  a(DE-B1597)503511  a(OCoLC)1038487474  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aML3521.U6 2004 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a781.643/09471 aUrban, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRussia Gets the Blues :bMusic, Culture, and Community in Unsettled Times /cMichael Urban. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b2 charts, 8 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCulture and Society after Socialism00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tCHAPTER ONE. Why Blues? -- tCHAPTER TWO. First Encounters -- tCHAPTER THREE. Moscow Blues: Musicians and Their Music -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Moscow Blues: Sites and Sounds -- tCHAPTER FIVE. St. Petersburg and the Provinces -- tCHAPTER SIX. Identity and Community -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Politics -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMichael Urban chronicles the advent of blues music in Russia and explores the significance of the genre in the turbulent, postcommunist society. Russians, he explains, have taken a music originating in the "low" culture of the American South and transformed it into an object of "high" culture, fashioning a social identity that distinguishes blues adherents from both the discredited Soviet past and the vulgar consumerism associated with the country's Westernization. While adapting the idiom to their own conditions, Russia's bliuzmeny (bluesmen) have absorbed the blues ethos encoded in the music by their American forebears, using it to invert their social world, thus deriving dignity and satisfaction from those very things that give one the blues.Based on more than forty interviews with blues musicians and fans, nightclub managers, and others, Russia Gets the Blues reveals the fascinating history of blues in Russia, from the initial mimicry of British blues-rock to the recent emergence of a specifically "Russian blues." The gradual mastering of the idiom in Russia has been conditioned by the culture of the country's intelligentsia, a fact explaining why, on one hand, bliuzmeny feel compelled to proselytize on behalf of the music, to share with others this treasure of "world culture," while, on the other, they perform blues almost exclusively in English—which almost no one understands—and condemn any and all efforts to make the music commercially successful.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBlues (Music)zRussia (Federation)xHistory and criticism. 0aPopular musiczRussia (Federation)y1991-2000xHistory and criticism. 4aAnthropology. 4aMusical Arts & Ethnomusicology. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aEvdokimov, Andrei.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171720840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501717208423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501717208/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK